<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM WALL</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov 27 19:19:22 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
The half dozen times that I have been to Washington, I have visited the Wall even though I knew no one who is honored on it.  Of course, it was still an awesome witness to me of the great dedication to duty of so too many persons!  It has taken on the significance of a shrine to me, somewhat like a cemetery.  I have read many of the names, and prayed with tears.  It was just last summer that a friend and I went to Springfield, Illinois to visit the various Lincoln sites.  While at Oak Ridge Cemetery, we came across a very dignified monument honoring those from Illinois who had given &quot;the last full measure&quot; in VietNam.  What would be the possibility of the other states doing likewise in the capitol cities?<br>
visited the Wall.  I did not know any of those personally wh<br>
o gave their lives in VietNam; but I am always awed at the<br>
sight of the Wall with too many names on it--yet a monument<br>
so necessary for the health of our citizens!<br>
As I begin to read the names on this shrine (somewhat like<br>
a cemetery marker) I pray through tears....<br>
July of 1995, I went with a friend to Springfield, Illinois<br>
to visit the Lincoln sites...at Oak Ridge Cemetery, we found<br>
a monument dedicated to those from Illinois...each branch of<br>
the service...who &quot;gave the last full measure&quot; in total<br>
dedication to duty in VietNam.  Why do not other capitol cities
